A Project Development and Environmental (PD&E) Study has been undertaken by the City of Minneola
for a proposed collector road that extends North Hancock Road to the north and then connects with US
27 to the west and Florida Turnpike to the east. As part of this planned connection, T.Y. Lin
International is contracted with Lake County for designing North Hancock Road from south of Old CR
50 to north of Fosgate Road (see Figure 1-1). The design considers widening Hancock Road from a
two-lane undivided road to a four-lane divided road and possible realignment at Old CR 50. To support
this design task, a traffic study was undertaken to evaluate possible lane configurations at three
intersections along this section of North Hancock Road, including:

The purpose of this traffic study is to support the design of North Hancock Road from
south of Old CR 50 to north of Fosgate Road, which is to be widened from a two-lane
undivided road to a four-lane divided road. This traffic study is conducted to identify
appropriate lane configurations at three intersections along this section of Hancock Road
and to evaluate the necessity of a traffic signal at North Hancock Road / Fosgate Road,

four-lane divided road, south of Old CR 50. Given the projected growth in the area, A
Project Development and Environmental (PD&E) Study has been undertaken by the City
of Minneola to study a new collector that extends North Hancock Road to the north and
then connects with US 27 to the west and connects with Florida Turnpike to the east via a
new interchange. This study effort was documented in a technical report: Minneola
Collector Road PD&E study – US 27 to Old CR 50 (HNTB, December 2008).
TY Lin international is contracted with Lake County for designing Hancock Road from
south of Old CR 50 to north of Fosgate Road. This design involves widening this section
of Hancock Road from a 2-lane undivided road to a four-lane divided road with appropriate
turn lane improvements at the intersections of North Hancock Road/Old CR 50 (East and
West) and North Hancock Road/Fosgate Road. Realignment of Old CR 50 between
Turkey Farm Road and Hancock Road is also considered as part of the design. Figure 1-
1 shows the concept, location, limits of the project.
To understand the existing traffic conditions and project future traffic volumes, traffic
counts, including eight 24-hour counts and three turning movement counts, were
conducted on March 24, 2009. Figure 2-1 depicts the locations of these counts. The
detailed count sheets are included in Appendix A.

The Minneola Collector Road PD&E study projected future traffic volumes based on the
Year 2025 CFRPM v4.1 FSUTMS model runs using the 2025 Cost Feasible Plan network.
The model network at this planning level was not sophisticated enough to account for all
roads in the network. For example, the intersection of North Hancock Road/Old CR 50
(west) was assumed as a three-leg intersection. However, this intersection is anticipated
to become a four-leg intersection providing access to the developments, east of North
Hancock Road. Moreover, Fosgate Road was not even reported in this study. As it comes
to the design phase, detailed intersection geometry needs to be determined. To meet this
design need, the design hour traffic volumes from Minneola Collector Road PD&E study
were used as a base and refined to reflect the possible intersection geometry due to some
new road connections proposed by the adjacent developments. These developments
Black West at Old CR 50 West, east of North Hancock Road
Imagine School at Minneola at Old CR 50 East, west of North Hancock Road
Hills of Minneola at Fosgate Road
 A new High School at the southeast corner of North Hancock Road/Fosgate
As a result of these developments, all three study intersections, currently three legs, would
be converted to four-leg intersections. Based on Minneola Collector Road PD&E study
and relevant information from the adjacent developments, the design hour turning
movement volumes at the three study intersections were derived and shown in Figures
2-2, 2-3, and 2-4 for 2010 Build 1, 2020 Build 2, and 2030 Build 2 conditions, respectively.
Worksheets supporting this future volume development are included in Appendix B.
A signal warrant analysis was performed in accordance with Chapter 4C, Manual on
Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD, 2003 Edition) at the intersection of North
Hancock Road (Turkey Farm Road) / Fosgate Road. The intersection currently has three
legs with a single lane for each approach. In the future, North Hancock Road (Turkey
Farm Road) will become a four-lane divided facility and the intersection will become a four-
leg intersection with the east leg, providing access to a planned high school and the Black
West development on the south and the Hills of Minneola on the north.
Warrants 1A, 1B, 2, 3, and 7 were evaluated under the 2009 existing conditions. It was
shown that none of these warrants are met under the 2009 existing conditions. Detailed
3.1.1.1 Warrant 1A. Eight-Hour Vehicular Volume (Minimum Vehicular Volume)
The Minimum Vehicular Volume, Condition A, is intended for application at locations
where a large volume of intersecting traffic is the principal reason to consider installing a
traffic control signal. The analysis is summarized in Table 3-1.
Lane Config: Major St: 1 lane; Minor St: 1 lane
As shown in Table 3-1, Warrant 1A is not currently met as there are no hours of volumes
exceeding the minimum hourly volume criteria for both Major Street and Minor Street, less
than the warranting threshold of 8 hours.
3.1.1.2 Warrant 1B. Eight-Hour Vehicular Volume (Interruption of Continuous Traffic)
The Interruption of Continuous Traffic, Condition B, is intended for application at locations
where Condition A is not satisfied and where the traffic volume on a major street is so
heavy that traffic on a minor intersecting street suffers excessive delay or conflict in
entering or crossing the major street. The analysis is summarized in Table 3-2.
Lane Config: Major St: 1 lane; Minor St: 1 lane
As shown in Table 3-2, Warrant 1B is not currently met as there are no hours of volumes
exceeding the minimum hourly volume criteria for both Major Street and Minor Street, less
than the warranting threshold of 8 hours.
The Four-Hour Vehicular Volume signal warrant conditions are intended to be applied
where the volume of intersecting traffic is the principal reason to consider installing a traffic
control signal. The analysis is shown in Figure 3-1.
As shown in Figure 3-1, the maximum major street volume (total of both approaches) is
191 vph; the maximum minor street volume (higher-volume approach) is 114 vph. The
area bounded by this two upper values falls outside of the plotted area and is below the
warranting curve. In other words, there are no hours of volume combinations that fall
above the warranting curve. Therefore, Warrant 2 is not currently met.
The Peak Hour signal warrant is intended for use at a location where traffic conditions are
such that for a minimum of 1 hour of an average day, the minor-street traffic suffers undue
delay when entering or crossing the major street.

In support of the design effort for widening and realignment of North Hancock Road, a
traffic operational analysis was performed at three intersections:
For this analysis, design hour turning movement volumes were derived from previous
studies conducted in this area. Based on the projected volumes, level of service analyses
were performed and lane configurations were determined at the three intersections. North
Hancock Road (Turkey Farm Road) / Fosgate Road is currently an unsignalized
intersection. A signal warrant analysis was also conducted to evaluate the necessity of a
Based on the traffic analyses, the following conclusions are drawn:
A traffic signal is not currently warranted at North Hancock Road (Turkey Farm
Road) / Fosgate Road. Given the projected traffic growth, a traffic signal would
be warranted at this intersection under 2020 and 2030 Build 2 conditions.
Based on the design hour volumes derived, travel lanes required at each study
intersection were determined for 2020 and 2030 Build 2 conditions:
At North Hancock Road / Fosgate Road
An exclusive northbound left turn lane
An exclusive northbound right turn lane
A exclusive southbound left turn lane
An exclusive eastbound left turn lane
At North Hancock Road / Old CR 50 (West) and North Hancock Road /
An exclusive northbound left turn lane
A exclusive southbound left turn lane
An exclusive eastbound left turn lane
An exclusive westbound left turn lane
